    <h2 id="basic-colors">Basic Colors</h2>
    <p><strong>红 (hóng)</strong> red, <strong>蓝 (lán)</strong> blue, <strong>绿 (lǜ)</strong> green, <strong>黄 (huáng)</strong> yellow, <strong>白 (bái)</strong> white, <strong>黑 (hēi)</strong> black, <strong>粉 (fěn)</strong> pink, <strong>紫 (zǐ)</strong> purple, <strong>橙 (chéng)</strong> orange, <strong>灰 (huī)</strong> gray. To say "color" in general, use 颜色 (yánsè).</p>

    <h2 id="symbolism">Color Symbolism</h2>
    <p><strong>Red</strong> represents luck and joy — used at weddings, New Year, and celebrations. <strong>White</strong> is associated with mourning and funerals, the opposite of Western wedding white. <strong>Yellow</strong> was historically the imperial color, reserved for the emperor. <strong>Green</strong> can have negative connotations — 戴绿帽子 (wearing a green hat) means being cheated on.</p>

    <h2 id="idioms">Color Idioms</h2>
    <p><strong>红红火火 (hóng hóng huǒ huǒ)</strong> — red and fiery, meaning prosperous. <strong>青出于蓝 (qīng chū yú lán)</strong> — blue comes from indigo but surpasses it, meaning the student surpasses the teacher. Explore more idioms with our <a href="/chinese/tools/daily-idiom/">Daily Idiom</a> tool.</p>

